data.content:
xUnit has no setup/teardown attributes. Here's the mapping:

| NUnit | xUnit equivalent |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |

Here's your converted code:

```csharp
// Class-level fixture for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Per-test setup via constructor, teardown via IDisposable
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** — xUnit creates `DatabaseFixture` once, shares it across all tests, then disposes it. Replaces `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`.
- **Constructor/`Dispose`** — xUnit creates a new test class instance per test, so the constructor replaces `[SetUp]` and `IDisposable.Dispose` replaces `[TearDown]`.
- **Assertions** — `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` → `Assert.NotNull(x)`, `Is.EqualTo` → `Assert.Equal` (expected comes first).
